The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | HUL beats odds to put up stellar show
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       HUL beats odds to put up stellar show
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Reaching out                                  
	Mumbai, July 25: Hindustan Unilever Ltd (HUL)  the countrys largest producer of fast-moving consumer goods such as soaps, detergents and toiletries  today beat the Streets expectations by posting a 13.2 per cent increase in net profit at Rs 558.18 crore for the second quarter ended June 30.        
	The household-goods maker saw demand surge even though it raised product prices to blunt inflation-stoked input prices.        
	Net sales grew 21 per cent to Rs 4,215.67 crore from the year-ago level of Rs 3,481.40 crore.        
	Net profits in the second quarter of this year included profits from the sale of property amounting to Rs 14.49 crore.         
	In the context of high cost inflation, the business is being managed dynamically using all available levers  cost management, enhanced mix and judicious pricing. We remain committed to sustaining long-term competitiveness of our business and value creation for shareholders, said chairman Harish Manwani.        
	The company raised the price of Surf Excel detergent this month after raising the prices of soaps earlier. Soaps and detergents account for about 46 per cent of the companys sales.        
	Manwani said soaring inflation hadnt dented sales but said the company would keep a close watch on petroleum prices.         
	Quoting an A.C Neilson survey, Manwani said urban consumer spending had grown 15 per cent while rural spending had grown 12 per cent despite the rise in product prices brought on by double-digit inflation.        
	During the quarter, the companys food business grew 14.1 per cent with good underlying volume growth. The company declared an interim dividend of Rs 3.50 per share.                                                                                                                                      
